On December 2, 2009, the Orange County Corrections Department received a complaint against Jones by a subordinate (victim) employee he supervised.  The victim alleged that she and Jones had engaged in a romantic relationship that lasted for approximately two years while he was her direct supervisor.  The victim stated that in May of 2009, after telling Jones she no longer wished to continue the relationship, Jones sexually harassed and touched her inappropriately.  The victim also alleged that Jones attempted to retaliate against her by issuing her a poor performance evaluation, which she claimed prevented her from obtaining approval for two training opportunities.  The victim stated that her complaint of retaliation was based upon one negative reprimand and her poor evaluation.  The victim entered into mediation for the discipline she received for the performance evaluation.  During the mediation, the victim never mentioned to the superior officer that she felt that the reprimand was based upon harassment or retaliation, just that she thought it was unfair.  The harassment allegations did not rise until after the victim was denied a training opportunity based in part on the subsequent evaluation.  The negative evaluation was based upon the victims failure to complete her investigations in a timely manner. The victim stated during her interview that she committed the conduct that resulted in her poor evaluation and Jones documented the victims performance deficiencies in email(s) wherein he requested completion of past due assignments.  The victim stated that there are no witnesses to the alleged unwanted sexual advances (comments/gestures) or improper touching and never told anyone in the office about the relationship.  Because there are no witnesses to the harassment, there is also no corroboration that there was intimidation or a hostile work environment.  During the investigation, Jones denied that there was a sexual relationship with the victim. However, Jones did admit to having mutual feelings for her, sexual conversations/emails with her, giving her gifts etc, but denied that any intimate acts occurred.  There is nothing to corroborate the victims allegation that she shared a physical relationship with Jones other than the emails admitted to by Jones.  Although the emails have certain sexual connotations, none of the emails confirm that any sexual activity actually occurred.  Even though this is a clear violation of agency policy, it does not fall within the parameters of a moral character violation outlined in Rule 11B-27.0011(4)(c)(4), F.A.C., therefore, Staff recommends no causing this case.  Legal concurs.
